            "abstractNote": "The diet of Myotis ricketti was examined by faecal analysis, and foraging behaviour was observed in the ﬁeld. Scales from at least three species of small ﬁsh were found in the droppings, together with fragments of insects from six orders. This study demonstrates that M. ricketti is a ﬁsh-eating bat. As with other trawling bats in the genus Myotis, M. ricketti emits short, broadband echolocation sounds. The sounds recorded from bats released from the hand swept downward from c. 70 to 28 kHz in 4 ms, and contained most energy at 41 kHz.",
